#chap-header("4", [= The Ritual Site], "Where the souls are taken")

The ritual site is where Šauhahten performs the soul extractions. It is a
mundane, grim location --- a cave in a rocky outcrop, screened by dense
undergrowth. The ugly work happens in an ugly place; the refined alchemy
happens elsewhere.

== Getting There

The party can reach the ritual site by following the trail from the dump
site (*Awareness D3* to pick it up, or automatic if they succeeded on the
Awareness D4 check at the dump site), or by following the peacekeeper's
directions into the area and exploring (*Investigate D3*).

#flavor[
  The Fog is thicker here. Not Dense --- not yet --- but present in a way it
  was not at the dump site. Wisps of it curl along the ground, pooling in
  depressions. The vegetation is wrong: bleached ferns, bark peeling in
  spirals, a smell like ozone and old copper. Something has been drawing
  Fog to this place, or the Fog has been drawn to what is happening here.
]

#attention[
  *Fog exposure:* The ritual site is close enough to the Fog boundary that
  the effects are noticeable. Mortal characters who spend more than an hour
  here should begin to feel uneasy --- headaches, a sense of being watched,
  mild disorientation. This is not yet mechanically dangerous (Dense Fog
  exposure requires sustained presence), but it should feel threatening.
  Deathless characters are less affected but may notice the Fog responding
  to the site in unusual ways --- eddying toward the cave mouth, thickening
  when they approach the ritual circle.
]

== The Scene

#aloud[
  The cave mouth is low and narrow, screened by brush that has been cut and
  replaced many times. Inside, the space opens into a rough chamber perhaps
  fifteen feet across. The stone floor has been swept clean, and you can
  see why: it is covered in scoring.

  Concentric circles have been carved into the rock, filled with a
  residue that catches the light --- pale, faintly luminescent. At the
  centre of the circles, iron stakes have been driven into the stone. The
  stakes are fitted with restraints. There are old stains on the
  restraints that do not need explanation.

  Along the cave walls, crude shelves hold alchemical apparatus: glass
  vessels, copper tubing, a distillation rig too heavy to move easily. Some
  of the vessels still contain residue --- a pale, oily substance that
  seems to move when you are not looking directly at it. The Fog curls into
  the cave and pools around the ritual circle, as if drawn to it.

  This place has been used many times.
]

== Investigating the Scene

- *Alchemy D4:* The residue in the ritual circles and the vessels is the
  byproduct of a sophisticated extraction process. This is not crude
  hedge-magic --- it is disciplined laboratory technique adapted for field
  conditions. The apparatus is improvised but competent. Whoever built this
  knows what they are doing.

- *Occultism D4:* What is being extracted here is the soul itself --- not
  life force, not magical energy, but the animating principle that
  distinguishes a person from a body. This is _not necromancy_. Necromancy
  manipulates the boundary between life and death; this process bypasses
  that boundary entirely, treating the soul as a substance to be distilled.
  The distinction is critical: it narrows the field of suspects
  dramatically.

- *Investigate D3:* The site has been used repeatedly over months. The
  scoring in the stone floor shows layers of ritual circles, each slightly
  refined from the last --- the perpetrator is iterating, improving the
  process. The restraints have been used at least a dozen times. The volume
  matches the number of missing persons from Keshto.

- *Awareness D3:* A trail leads from the cave toward the dump site (if not
  already found). A second trail leads in a _third_ direction --- southwest,
  away from both the dump site and Keshto. This trail goes cold after a
  few hundred yards: the perpetrator has deliberately obscured it,
  brushing away tracks and using Fog cover. Whatever is at the end of
  that trail, finding it will require different information.

- *Occultism D5 or Alchemy D5:* The ritual technique is recognisable to
  anyone with specific knowledge. The circle geometry, the extraction
  methodology, the treatment of the soul as an alchemical substance ---
  this is derived from Mortefactor research. Not standard Mortefactor
  practice, but an extension or perversion of techniques developed by the
  Most Ancient and Noble Order.

#note[
  This last check is the pivotal clue that sends the party back to Keshto
  Village. If no one in the party can make this check, provide the
  information through other means: a symbol carved into the cave wall that
  matches Mortefactor iconography (recognisable with *Occultism D3* or
  *Lore D3*), or a discarded journal page with technical notes in a
  scholarly hand that references "the Order's foundations."

  The adventure _requires_ the party to make the Mortefactor connection.
  Do not let it hinge on a single high-DC check.
]

#note[
  *What both sites together tell the party:*
  - The full scope of the operation: at least eleven victims, extracted over
    months, with increasing frequency.
  - The method is alchemical and scholarly --- not bestial, not divine,
    not necromantic.
  - The perpetrator is methodical, skilled, and iterating.
  - Neither the dump site nor the ritual site is where the perpetrator
    lives. They come, work, and leave.
  - The technique is Mortefactor-derived --- this sends the party back to
    Keshto to pull on the faction thread.
]

#attention[
  *System lesson for this location:* Exploration in hazardous terrain.
  The ritual site is the party's introduction to Fog proximity, environmental
  awareness, and the idea that the world beyond the Clears is actively
  dangerous. Use the Fog to create atmosphere and mild pressure, but do not
  punish the party mechanically for being here --- save that for later
  adventures when they venture deeper.
]
